===Etymology===
From earlier {{m|en|Tayuan}}, {{m|en|Tayoan}}, or other variants, from {{der|en|fos|tau||people}} + {{m|fos|an||place}}. Recorded in {{cog|nl|-}} as {{m|nl|Tayouan}} (and other variants), and in {{cog|nan|-}} as {{m|zh|大員|tr=Tāi-oân}} (and other variants).<ref>{{cite-web |last=Mair |first=V. H. |authorlink=Victor H. Mair |date=2010 |work=How to Forget Your Mother Tongue and Remember Your National Language |url=http://www.pinyin.info/readings/mair/taiwanese.html}}</ref> The term initially referred to a sandy peninsula in the area of modern-day {{w|Anping District}}, [[Tainan]], and eventually became the name of the entire island. See also {{zh-l|臺灣}}.

